<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-03-16T05:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-03-16T05:00:00-05:00" n="158" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d158">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">852.00/4948: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Consul at Gibraltar</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Williams</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Gibraltar</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-03-16T10:00:00+00:00">March 16, 1937—10
                                a.m.</date><lb/>[Received March 16—7:05 a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>The following information was given British Intelligence Service by an
                            Englishman who had deserted Spanish Government forces and who came to
                            Gibraltar a few days ago from Castellon.</p>
                        <p>On February 18th an American battalion 450 strong arrived near Chinchon
                            between Madrid and Valencia. Said to be fully armed and equipped. He
                            added that he had been wounded, and cared for at an American dressing
                            station February 23rd 50 kilometres behind the lines.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Williams</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
